03:39.071 --> 03:40.890
MAN ON RADIO: <i>As the saying
goes here in Maine,</i>

03:40.915 --> 03:43.305
<i>if you don't like the weather,
just wait a minute...</i>

03:43.330 --> 03:44.331
<i>[tuning radio]</i>

03:45.034 --> 03:46.868
<i>[scanning stations]</i>

03:46.893 --> 03:49.160
WOMAN: <i>The governor
said private prisons bring...</i>

03:49.185 --> 03:53.104
MAN: <i>Right here on WXIU,
Brumberg-Castle Rock...</i>

03:53.173 --> 03:55.885
<i>[operatic singing]</i>

04:03.934 --> 04:06.020
[food sizzling]

04:11.940 --> 04:15.734
Don't tell me... breakfast in bed?

04:15.946 --> 04:17.613
[man grunts]

04:17.615 --> 04:20.326
I wish you'd taken that
buyout 30 years ago.

04:23.245 --> 04:25.706
- After you, Mrs. Lacy.
- Oh! [laughs]

04:27.640 --> 04:29.599
- Will there be a cake?
- No.

04:29.624 --> 04:32.918
It's not really a cake... crowd.

04:33.005 --> 04:35.757
Penny's driving me to Portland.
I'm buying new shorts.

04:35.883 --> 04:38.676
I told her, "Dale retires, we're
gonna find out once and for all

04:38.677 --> 04:41.054
- if he's got knees."
- Hmm.

04:41.055 --> 04:43.723
That's easy for you to say,
you won't have to look at them.

04:43.724 --> 04:46.268
[laughing] Last day, Mr. Lacy.

05:00.491 --> 05:02.826
<i>[operatic duet playing]</i>

05:14.171 --> 05:16.423
[bell ringing]

05:18.133 --> 05:20.636
<i>[opera duet continues]</i>

05:46.328 --> 05:48.664
<i>[opera duet continues]</i>

06:04.305 --> 06:06.140
[music stops]

06:07.641 --> 06:09.476
[bird chittering]

06:38.547 --> 06:39.965
[birds chirping]

06:44.470 --> 06:47.138
[engine revving]

06:47.139 --> 06:48.390
[twig snaps]

06:54.063 --> 06:56.315
[dog panting]

06:59.651 --> 07:01.653
[dog barking]

07:10.370 --> 07:12.997
[tires screeching]

07:12.998 --> 07:14.083
[engine revving]

07:17.044 --> 07:18.378
[grunt]

07:29.932 --> 07:32.768
<i>♪♪</i>

07:59.795 --> 08:02.256
<i>♪♪</i>

08:24.778 --> 08:26.488
[bell ringing]

08:29.700 --> 08:31.869
[men chattering]

08:45.674 --> 08:47.911
- [door clanks shut]
- [bell rings]

08:47.936 --> 08:49.895
Some folks aren't built for retirement,

08:49.920 --> 08:51.713
same deal as my old man.

08:51.738 --> 08:54.083
Finished his twenty in the Navy,

08:54.191 --> 08:56.609
- dead in a year.
- That a fact?

08:56.727 --> 08:59.711
MAN: My point is, it wasn't
the smoothest shift change,

08:59.766 --> 09:01.814
but we're damn glad to have you.

09:01.815 --> 09:02.900
[door buzzes]

09:06.862 --> 09:09.071
- [phone ringing]
- Little trivia.

09:09.072 --> 09:12.408
Shawshank's actually
lost four wardens in office.

09:12.409 --> 09:14.619
You can still see
the bullet hole where Warden...

09:14.620 --> 09:17.289
- We can skip the audio tour.
- All right.

09:23.128 --> 09:25.505
DEPUTY WARDEN: You know,
they never found the head.

09:25.506 --> 09:27.340
Heard they got a deal on the funeral.

09:27.341 --> 09:29.133
Ten percent off.

09:29.134 --> 09:31.702
- [imitates slicing noise]
- [woman groans]

09:31.790 --> 09:34.667
If this were my office,
I'd kill myself too.

09:34.792 --> 09:36.418
It's yours now.

09:36.451 --> 09:38.351
Boost enrollment by 20 percent,

09:38.429 --> 09:41.384
we can get an extra 1.5 million a year.

09:41.524 --> 09:43.734
We can always park
non-violents in the gym.

09:43.798 --> 09:46.084
Actually, the gym's
already double-bunk, ma'am.

09:46.109 --> 09:47.443
The whole prison is.

09:47.444 --> 09:48.695
Thank you, Officer.

09:49.780 --> 09:50.957
Of course.

09:51.050 --> 09:53.282
Except for block F,
but that's been closed

09:53.283 --> 09:55.105
since the Christmas fire in '87.

09:55.494 --> 09:58.956
- Officer...?
- Zaleski, ma'am.

10:02.868 --> 10:04.618
How many beds in block F?

10:04.752 --> 10:06.753
Sixty, seventy, at least.

10:06.849 --> 10:09.726
But, I mean, nobody goes down
there anymore.

10:10.637 --> 10:12.501
You're telling me
that my predecessor left

10:12.526 --> 10:15.993
an entire wing of this prison
unoccupied for 30 years?

10:16.501 --> 10:18.024
Why?

10:18.548 --> 10:20.142
ZALESKI: He had a severance package

10:20.181 --> 10:22.580
from Northeast Correctional
that was six figures.

10:22.605 --> 10:24.064
That's on top of his pension.

10:24.089 --> 10:25.923
- So?
- So?

10:25.948 --> 10:28.526
- Why did he off himself?
- Who am I, Sigmund Freud?

10:28.527 --> 10:30.695
I don't know, sometimes
a rope is just a fuckin' rope.

10:30.696 --> 10:33.282
[welding torch screeches]

10:35.701 --> 10:37.494
[clanking]

10:47.428 --> 10:49.096
[radio plays softly]

10:50.825 --> 10:52.452
Holy shit.

10:55.136 --> 10:56.678
Right here,

10:56.773 --> 10:58.357
that's where they stacked the bodies.

10:58.506 --> 11:00.758
Fuckin' jailbird barbecue.

11:03.125 --> 11:06.044
Yeah. Mm-hmm.

11:06.257 --> 11:08.259
All right, bro, that's night-nights.

11:09.349 --> 11:11.893
- Really?
- Oh, fuck, yeah.

11:13.363 --> 11:16.309
- Great. Thanks.
- Do you want in?

11:16.574 --> 11:20.203
No. We're supposed to count the beds.

11:33.062 --> 11:34.896
Hey!

11:35.022 --> 11:36.399
Somebody's been here.

11:38.764 --> 11:40.641
[footsteps]

12:09.920 --> 12:11.963
<i>♪♪</i>

12:15.871 --> 12:17.148
Hello?

12:36.113 --> 12:39.491
[clanking]

12:40.287 --> 12:41.955
[creaking]

13:04.057 --> 13:05.934
[metallic creaking]

13:10.522 --> 13:12.065
[grunts]

13:24.411 --> 13:26.469
- [thud]
- Ah, shit.

13:30.536 --> 13:31.829
Great.

13:33.503 --> 13:34.838
[grunts]

13:41.553 --> 13:42.971
[exhales]

13:57.486 --> 13:59.154
Hello?

14:37.817 --> 14:39.611
[water dripping]

14:50.757 --> 14:52.508
Oh, fuck!

14:52.595 --> 14:55.306
<i>♪♪</i>

15:00.507 --> 15:02.717
[alarm wailing]

15:04.511 --> 15:07.121
- [clanking, alarm wailing]
- GUARD: Counting!

15:07.226 --> 15:13.563
8172, 8369, 8462, 8172, 8369...

15:13.627 --> 15:17.129
- Cell block A, full block.
- Holbeck?

15:17.290 --> 15:19.276
- Block B.
- GUARD 2: All accounted for!

15:20.610 --> 15:22.988
<i>♪♪</i>

15:26.030 --> 15:28.406
GUARD: I need a name, son.

15:28.618 --> 15:30.624
Who are you?

15:30.870 --> 15:32.984
What's your name, hmm?

15:33.687 --> 15:35.921
We got no records of you.

15:37.265 --> 15:39.129
Come on, what's your name?

15:42.299 --> 15:44.050
How'd you get inside this prison?

15:47.804 --> 15:49.347
Cat got your tongue?

15:51.766 --> 15:53.727
Who put you down that hole?

15:55.551 --> 15:56.844
You can tell me.

16:01.281 --> 16:02.491
Nothin', huh?

16:04.563 --> 16:06.106
All right.

16:07.240 --> 16:09.284
[device beeping]

16:12.871 --> 16:14.789
[suspenseful music]

16:21.087 --> 16:23.881
<i>♪♪</i>

16:23.882 --> 16:27.051
<i>[distant PA announcement]</i>

16:27.052 --> 16:28.927
- [convicts yelling]
- [man whistles]

16:28.928 --> 16:31.528
MAN: <i>What did he say when you found him?</i>

16:31.780 --> 16:33.948
ZALESKI: <i>The kid? Didn't say a word.</i>

16:33.973 --> 16:35.724
<i>- He's like a mute.
- Hey.</i>

16:38.438 --> 16:41.107
<i>[indistinct PA announcement]</i>

16:42.108 --> 16:43.901
It's a shower.

16:43.902 --> 16:46.279
To-To clean? Water?

16:47.525 --> 16:49.109
It's okay.

16:49.211 --> 16:50.337
It's okay.

17:01.226 --> 17:02.560
GUARD: Oh!

17:02.644 --> 17:03.964
What the fuck is this thing anyway?

17:04.000 --> 17:06.617
- It's like a...
- [clank]

17:06.875 --> 17:08.550
It's like an old water tank?

17:11.898 --> 17:13.775
Jesus Christ.

17:13.800 --> 17:15.743
What do you think it does to a guy?

17:15.829 --> 17:17.038
What?

17:17.086 --> 17:20.665
Bein' here... trapped, alone.

17:21.479 --> 17:22.854
I don't know.

17:22.910 --> 17:24.786
Saw a kid do two weeks in the hole,

17:24.810 --> 17:27.259
came out thinkin'
he was the Easter bunny.

17:27.304 --> 17:28.735
[laughs]

17:29.158 --> 17:30.588
It's funny?

17:35.760 --> 17:38.137
ZALESKI: Hey, there was a big coffee can

17:38.170 --> 17:40.380
full of cigarette butts right here.

17:43.253 --> 17:45.171
Do you see that anywhere?

17:52.387 --> 17:54.513
[sighs]

17:54.514 --> 17:57.607
GUARD: <i>Okay, one old perv
in charge of a prison</i>

17:57.632 --> 18:01.844
plus one fuck slave,
in an oil tank, minus one head.

18:01.987 --> 18:03.946
How's my math on that?

18:04.065 --> 18:05.816
DEPUTY WARDEN:
<i>He's never been processed,</i>

18:05.817 --> 18:07.846
not even a jaywalking charge.

18:08.374 --> 18:10.333
No fingerprints in the system.

18:10.685 --> 18:13.480
WARDEN: This is
a public relations disaster.

18:15.323 --> 18:18.535
So, do we call the cops,
or the board of directors?

18:20.665 --> 18:24.290
Why don't we... take a beat.

18:24.696 --> 18:26.883
Sort out what we're dealing with here

18:26.984 --> 18:28.527
before we make any calls.

18:29.007 --> 18:30.382
ZALESKI: <i>Hey.</i>

18:30.383 --> 18:31.717
If they can't figure out who he is,

18:31.718 --> 18:33.207
they gotta let him go, right?

18:33.269 --> 18:36.176
Yeah, I'm sure they'll make him
the mayor of Castle Rock.

18:37.405 --> 18:38.490
[clank]

18:41.144 --> 18:43.187
<i>♪♪</i>

18:43.188 --> 18:46.223
GUARD: <i>If he wasn't
a psychopath before...</i>

18:46.381 --> 18:48.549
<i>he sure as shit is now.</i>

18:54.011 --> 18:55.553
GUARD: <i>I'll tell you one thing.</i>

18:55.704 --> 18:57.659
I wouldn't want to be the new warden.

18:57.660 --> 18:58.703
<i>[buzzer]</i>

19:10.423 --> 19:13.176
Young man, who are you?

19:16.471 --> 19:17.639
What's your name?

19:20.100 --> 19:22.640
Can he hear me?
Have we checked out his ears?

19:22.936 --> 19:25.104
Or are we playing some kind
of fuckin' charades here,

19:25.105 --> 19:26.523
- because...
- [mouthing words]

19:32.403 --> 19:34.197
Henry Deaver.

19:36.783 --> 19:38.451
WARDEN: <i>Okay.</i>

19:39.911 --> 19:41.704
That's not Henry Deaver.

19:43.250 --> 19:44.668
Who the fuck's Henry Deaver?

19:46.376 --> 19:47.669
It's a long story.

19:52.103 --> 19:53.854
Henry...

19:53.925 --> 19:56.391
Matthew...

19:56.841 --> 19:58.093
Deaver.

20:01.224 --> 20:04.643
<i>♪♪</i>

20:04.644 --> 20:07.564
MAN: <i>How much doubt is reasonable?</i>

20:11.484 --> 20:13.403
Well, folks...

20:14.231 --> 20:18.883
If I had to choose whether
or not to take someone's life...

20:19.659 --> 20:21.219
and that is the choice before you today,

20:21.244 --> 20:23.148
make no mistake...

20:24.080 --> 20:26.610
I don't think <i>any</i> amount
would seem reasonable.

20:27.000 --> 20:28.602
Now, me,

20:28.942 --> 20:31.063
I had to kill someone?

20:31.462 --> 20:32.969
[scoffs]

20:33.041 --> 20:36.797
I'd need it etched in gold
and signed by God Himself.

20:37.619 --> 20:39.867
We're talking about an abused woman,

20:41.097 --> 20:42.938
linked to the death
of her husband Richard Chambers

20:42.963 --> 20:45.632
by purely circumstantial evidence.

20:47.818 --> 20:49.819
We're talking about
a disbarred alcoholic

20:49.874 --> 20:52.125
who represented Leanne
in her first trial,

20:52.220 --> 20:54.680
and a star witness who was
a known drug trafficker

20:54.736 --> 20:55.891
with a sweetheart deal.

20:55.954 --> 20:59.086
All that, I'd say,
adds up to some doubt.

21:00.470 --> 21:03.681
That was enough for a retrial,
a do-over.

21:03.812 --> 21:05.498
This...

21:05.663 --> 21:08.241
sentencing phase, it's a do-over, too.

21:09.042 --> 21:12.976
But after today,
there will be no more do-overs.

21:14.907 --> 21:16.991
Judge signs an order,

21:17.125 --> 21:19.166
needle goes into a vein,

21:19.234 --> 21:21.318
the body goes into a box,

21:21.429 --> 21:23.213
and in six hours,

21:23.890 --> 21:25.058
that body...

21:27.852 --> 21:29.729
<i>that</i> body...

21:30.772 --> 21:33.017
will be ashes.

21:34.234 --> 21:37.278
And ashes don't get appeals
in the state of Texas.

21:39.614 --> 21:40.907
So I ask...

21:43.952 --> 21:46.454
how much doubt are you folks
comfortable with?

21:48.662 --> 21:51.539
[angry shouting]

21:51.564 --> 21:54.257
REPORTER: <i>...who was
sentenced to death in 1993</i>

21:54.295 --> 21:57.883
<i>is the oldest death row inmate
in the state of Texas.</i>

21:57.942 --> 22:00.944
<i>The execution is scheduled
for 6 o' clock this evening.</i>

22:00.999 --> 22:02.688
Whoa, whoa, whoa, you can't be here.

22:02.713 --> 22:04.505
I'm the lawyer.

22:04.599 --> 22:06.810
[protesters continue shouting]

22:08.309 --> 22:10.103
<i>[bell ringing]</i>

22:24.117 --> 22:26.119
Fifth Circuit's gonna rule against us.

22:28.571 --> 22:31.114
I'm sorry, Leanne.

22:31.249 --> 22:33.272
[sighs] The governor is a long shot.

22:33.376 --> 22:35.327
- LEANNE: You know?
- But...

22:35.967 --> 22:39.975
I grew up downwind
from a cereal factory.

22:40.675 --> 22:42.635
A mile from home.

22:43.636 --> 22:46.055
Smelled like Cheerios.

22:47.348 --> 22:49.183
That was my first memory.

22:52.061 --> 22:53.604
What's yours?

22:54.793 --> 22:57.754
- What?
- Your first memory.

23:00.877 --> 23:03.478
[Gene Pitney] <i>♪ I was only ♪</i>

23:03.546 --> 23:06.991
<i>♪ 24 hours from Tulsa ♪</i>

23:07.049 --> 23:08.676
<i>[car door slams]</i>

23:09.719 --> 23:11.429
Gene Pitney.

23:11.596 --> 23:13.723
"24 Hours from Tulsa."

23:18.102 --> 23:20.252
That's a nice song.

23:20.354 --> 23:22.315
"24 Hours from Tulsa."

23:23.316 --> 23:25.241
My dad...

23:25.318 --> 23:27.110
used to take me to a honky-tonk place

23:27.111 --> 23:29.112
on the south side of Dallas.

23:29.113 --> 23:31.114
He'd get good and drunk and take me

23:31.115 --> 23:33.450
to the alligator farm just next door.

23:33.576 --> 23:36.606
We'd sit there and stare
at those gators for two,

23:36.661 --> 23:38.746
three hours at a time.

23:38.873 --> 23:41.208
Sometimes I'd get to drive the car home

23:41.209 --> 23:42.543
at the end of the night.

23:45.171 --> 23:47.342
What I keep wondering,

23:47.632 --> 23:49.549
all the smells we smell

23:50.131 --> 23:53.389
and the... songs and pictures...

23:53.930 --> 23:55.680
do you lose them all?

23:56.265 --> 23:57.399
I mean,

23:57.558 --> 23:59.719
wherever you go next,

24:00.019 --> 24:01.811
does the tape get erased?

24:02.172 --> 24:04.345
And if it does...

24:05.900 --> 24:08.444
you're not really you anymore, are ya?

24:11.739 --> 24:13.908
Is that what you're afraid of?

24:16.410 --> 24:18.746
That's what I want.

24:21.415 --> 24:23.834
<i>♪♪</i>

24:27.338 --> 24:28.972
MAN: <i>Look at me.</i>

24:29.034 --> 24:32.259
Look at me. I'm Alan.
I'm a friend of your mother's.

24:32.260 --> 24:33.969
["24 Hours from Tulsa"
playing on car radio]

24:33.970 --> 24:36.136
No frostbite.

24:36.264 --> 24:37.848
You been inside somewhere?

24:55.992 --> 24:57.702
[monitor beeping]

25:08.671 --> 25:11.674
[beeping slows]

25:15.594 --> 25:18.222
[beeping fades]

25:25.730 --> 25:27.356
[man, indistinct]

25:31.444 --> 25:34.336
[alarm wails]

25:34.383 --> 25:36.699
- What's goin' on?
- She's alive again!

25:37.546 --> 25:38.630
HENRY: What...

25:40.494 --> 25:42.119
- Hey!
- [beeping, alarm wailing]

25:42.305 --> 25:43.673
Hey, I'm her witness.

25:43.789 --> 25:45.749
You don't get a fucking do-over!

25:45.750 --> 25:48.210
[shouting, indistinct]

25:49.855 --> 25:51.338
...fuckin' witness!

25:51.455 --> 25:53.132
- [alarm continues]
- Hey!

26:03.017 --> 26:04.477
[tires squeal]

26:13.319 --> 26:15.196
[car departs]

26:17.374 --> 26:19.334
MAN: <i>Henry Matthew Deaver.</i>

26:19.583 --> 26:22.660
Based out of Houston,
grew up 20 miles that way,

26:22.731 --> 26:24.075
Castle Rock.

26:24.163 --> 26:25.802
Bad reputation.

26:25.915 --> 26:28.166
Big mess with the state police
when he was a kid.

26:28.728 --> 26:32.017
<i>Pulled some stunt, ran away from home.</i>

26:32.171 --> 26:34.470
<i>People thought somebody took him.</i>

26:34.632 --> 26:36.508
<i>Half the state's out looking for him.</i>

26:36.509 --> 26:37.900
<i>Middle of winter.</i>

26:38.010 --> 26:40.307
<i>And what they find is his father.</i>

26:40.429 --> 26:43.010
<i>Half-froze, and his back's broken.</i>

26:43.185 --> 26:45.706
<i>Doesn't last three days.</i>

26:46.519 --> 26:49.229
<i>Kid comes sashaying back
from the dead like Tom Sawyer</i>

26:49.230 --> 26:53.347
<i>to find out he's got no dad,
and the town blames him.</i>

26:53.717 --> 26:56.302
<i>Claimed he couldn't remember a thing.</i>

26:56.570 --> 26:58.860
WARDEN: So, our anonymous friend
says exactly three words,

26:58.948 --> 27:01.367
and we think that he's asking
for his lawyer?

27:03.762 --> 27:06.720
I think we are not bringing
a criminal defense attorney

27:06.790 --> 27:09.477
into an internal
corporate matter. Mnh-mnh.

27:09.542 --> 27:12.118
We could take him for a drive.
Drop him over the border.

27:12.169 --> 27:13.360
Yeah, then he pulls a Willie Horton

27:13.385 --> 27:14.712
and I spend the rest of my career

27:14.713 --> 27:15.840
in accounts receivable.

27:20.302 --> 27:22.137
Or we could find him a roomie.

27:22.459 --> 27:26.287
A psycho who collects
life sentences. Circle of life.

27:31.564 --> 27:32.773
[chicken clucking]

27:37.987 --> 27:40.114
[chicken squawking]

27:47.204 --> 27:49.665
[wings clank against fence]

27:53.502 --> 27:55.045
[hissing]

28:04.889 --> 28:06.765
- [squawking]
- [alligator hissing]

28:12.188 --> 28:14.064
[cellphone chiming]

28:17.036 --> 28:18.662
Hello?

28:20.473 --> 28:21.931
Yeah.

28:22.025 --> 28:24.033
Yeah, Henry Matthew Deaver the attorney.

28:26.535 --> 28:28.453
What? I-I can't hear you.

28:28.454 --> 28:30.623
<i>[man talking, indistinct]</i>

28:32.750 --> 28:34.260
Whoever you've got isn't my client.

28:34.330 --> 28:35.767
My clients are all dead.

28:35.836 --> 28:37.450
Look, I shouldn't even be calling you,

28:37.493 --> 28:40.239
but listen, listen,
they found a kid in a cage.

28:42.718 --> 28:44.390
No one else is gonna help him.

28:44.470 --> 28:46.096
Shawshank State Prison.

28:47.556 --> 28:49.307
[crowing]

28:49.308 --> 28:50.851
Who... Who is this?

29:00.319 --> 29:03.030
<i>♪♪</i>

29:23.842 --> 29:26.804
<i>[rock music playing on car radio]</i>

29:32.518 --> 29:34.235
BOY: The MILF.

29:35.342 --> 29:37.343
Twice in one month?

29:37.439 --> 29:40.659
If I find out you've been...
subcontracting me...

29:40.720 --> 29:43.437
What? You'll tell your homeroom teacher?

29:45.239 --> 29:48.575
It's for me. I've got a condition.

29:51.412 --> 29:54.012
Oh, yeah, I can get you rest
on Thursday or...

29:54.081 --> 29:55.551
a postdated check if you want.

29:55.624 --> 29:58.252
Obamacare's been repealed. No co-pays.

29:59.378 --> 30:00.921
Forty gets you eight fives.

30:05.259 --> 30:08.546
- You need kids, by the way.
- What?

30:08.762 --> 30:11.054
- To be a MILF.
- [laughs]

30:13.196 --> 30:14.614
See you around.

30:23.402 --> 30:25.404
[rock music blaring]

30:42.209 --> 30:43.794
DRIVER: Here you go.

30:47.009 --> 30:48.510
[distant chatter]

31:14.627 --> 31:17.003
RADIO: <i>...by the power that is our Lord.</i>

31:17.090 --> 31:19.134
[sermon continues on radio]

31:43.107 --> 31:45.109
<i>♪♪</i>

31:59.706 --> 32:01.583
[indistinct shouting]

32:07.089 --> 32:08.424
Hey, killer.

32:31.039 --> 32:32.916
HENRY: What the hell?

32:34.587 --> 32:35.922
[thud]

32:45.002 --> 32:47.713
[man speaking in distance]

32:49.826 --> 32:53.387
MAN: <i>...9-12 says,
"But two are better than one,</i>

32:53.564 --> 32:57.109
<i>"because they have
a good return on their labor.</i>

32:57.219 --> 32:59.261
<i>If either of them falls down,</i>

32:59.349 --> 33:02.402
<i>one can help the other up.</i>

33:02.540 --> 33:05.500
<i>But pity anyone who falls..."</i>

33:05.649 --> 33:07.109
ALAN: <i>It was minus-forty last night.</i>

33:09.429 --> 33:10.888
You know how cold that is?

33:12.677 --> 33:14.929
Freeze to death in an hour.

33:15.032 --> 33:17.784
And you've been gone, like, 11 days.

33:20.412 --> 33:22.080
So what happened out there?

33:26.768 --> 33:28.353
I don't remember.

33:29.379 --> 33:31.422
[sighs]

33:31.447 --> 33:34.325
Son, do you know what happened
to your father?

33:40.011 --> 33:41.310
Okay.

33:45.395 --> 33:46.688
[slams]

34:02.412 --> 34:04.998
<i>♪♪</i>

34:14.216 --> 34:15.884
[crying]

34:18.480 --> 34:19.856
Henry!

34:33.485 --> 34:35.904
[fire alarm beeping]

34:36.768 --> 34:38.020
Hello?

34:41.507 --> 34:43.342
[TV playing]

34:43.382 --> 34:44.841
HENRY: Mom?

34:44.880 --> 34:47.299
- [fire alarm sounding]
- [hissing]

34:47.393 --> 34:49.188
[groans]

34:53.672 --> 34:55.799
[alarm continues]

35:06.768 --> 35:08.437
HENRY: Mom?

35:09.521 --> 35:11.106
Ruth?

35:12.107 --> 35:14.672
Oh! My, uh...

35:14.735 --> 35:16.778
my white oaks are dead.

35:18.590 --> 35:20.215
It's a miracle they didn't topple over

35:20.240 --> 35:21.767
and kill someone.

35:21.825 --> 35:24.290
Did you bring your own chainsaw?

35:24.375 --> 35:27.664
Well, then, let's check the garage.

35:28.610 --> 35:31.863
Come on now!
We were all immigrants once.

35:31.919 --> 35:34.292
Except Sitting Bull. [laughs]

35:34.337 --> 35:36.379
I'm not like the others.

35:36.506 --> 35:40.073
- I adopted a black son.
- Mom. Mom.

35:40.593 --> 35:43.678
It's me. I'm Henry.

35:43.805 --> 35:45.641
I called you this morning.

35:47.726 --> 35:49.411
Henry.

35:49.522 --> 35:51.357
Yeah, of course you are.

35:52.397 --> 35:53.857
Okay.

36:05.994 --> 36:07.995
I had to fly in for a...

36:08.045 --> 36:09.733
a work thing.

36:09.831 --> 36:12.186
But I wanted to see you.

36:12.459 --> 36:14.522
Maris watching the baby?

36:14.753 --> 36:16.797
Wendell is fifteen, Mom.

36:19.437 --> 36:20.687
What...

36:20.759 --> 36:22.501
W-What happened to the nurse?

36:22.556 --> 36:24.529
- Who?
- Your Medicare pays

36:24.554 --> 36:25.743
for a home health aide.

36:25.768 --> 36:27.970
I arranged it all with St. Jude's.

36:28.936 --> 36:32.189
Oh! Constance. Long gone.

36:32.296 --> 36:34.009
Gone? Where?

36:34.071 --> 36:38.035
Well, I'd like to say heaven,
but I have my suspicions.

36:38.068 --> 36:39.611
[thudding]

36:40.779 --> 36:42.322
Is someone in the house?

36:43.615 --> 36:45.158
Someone's in the house?

36:46.660 --> 36:49.162
- [thudding]
- [TV playing]

36:50.372 --> 36:53.086
ALAN: Are we on fire?

36:53.220 --> 36:57.109
You know, there's easier ways
to get a man out of the shower.

37:00.786 --> 37:03.371
Henry, do you know Alan Pangborn?

37:03.427 --> 37:06.148
He's our county sheriff.

37:06.513 --> 37:07.835
Was.

37:08.140 --> 37:10.892
- Been a few years now, Ruth.
- Alan?

37:12.210 --> 37:14.378
W-What's going on?

37:14.521 --> 37:17.189
You boys must be hungry.
How about some bacon and eggs?

37:17.190 --> 37:18.983
Why don't you see if you can scare up

37:18.984 --> 37:21.342
some fresh sheets for your boy?

37:21.445 --> 37:23.272
- If he's stayin'.
- RUTH: Yeah.

37:23.772 --> 37:25.449
Few days.

37:26.908 --> 37:28.967
What brings you home?

37:29.220 --> 37:32.401
- A client.
- Oh, yeah?

37:32.460 --> 37:35.003
You've burned through
all the killers in Texas?

37:35.542 --> 37:38.737
So, what is this, Alan? You livin' here?

37:38.920 --> 37:41.175
Frequent flyer.

37:41.381 --> 37:45.196
Your mother and I enjoy
one another's companionship.

37:45.385 --> 37:47.876
And my father's shirts, you...

37:48.013 --> 37:50.024
enjoy those, too?

37:50.140 --> 37:52.212
I don't think he's gonna miss it.

37:52.309 --> 37:53.652
Where is he?

37:53.935 --> 37:56.198
- Who?
- My father.

37:56.772 --> 37:58.481
- Oh...
- I stopped by the church,

37:58.482 --> 38:00.534
and the cemetery is... is gone.

38:00.585 --> 38:03.170
Yeah, the church made
some wildcat investments,

38:03.195 --> 38:05.797
didn't pan out, had to parcel the land.

38:05.868 --> 38:07.703
So they... just...

38:07.783 --> 38:09.328
paved over the bodies?

38:09.383 --> 38:10.930
No, they moved 'em.

38:11.023 --> 38:14.900
To a yard up in Banner, by the airport.

38:14.956 --> 38:18.834
My experience,
the dead are not particular.

38:18.888 --> 38:20.795
They can't do
that without our permission.

38:20.841 --> 38:23.006
- You mother gave it.
- [scoffs]

38:26.301 --> 38:28.219
Nobody thought to pick up
the phone and call me?

38:28.293 --> 38:30.222
Did she even know
what she was signing for?

38:32.651 --> 38:34.193
You signed for her.

38:34.254 --> 38:37.229
I deposited the distress
settlement for her, too.

38:39.231 --> 38:41.107
What else you been signing for, Alan?

38:41.108 --> 38:43.110
[footsteps approach]

38:48.490 --> 38:50.325
Oh! The sheets!

38:55.288 --> 38:58.041
<i>♪♪</i>

39:02.712 --> 39:04.256
<i>[squeaking]</i>

39:40.250 --> 39:42.294
- [snap]
- [mice squeals]

39:45.964 --> 39:47.382
[door buzzer]

39:53.555 --> 39:55.264
[buzzing]

39:55.265 --> 39:56.391
Family?

39:59.175 --> 40:01.510
- Client.
- Inmate's name.

40:01.605 --> 40:02.813
I don't have it.

40:02.879 --> 40:05.563
You're a lawyer and you don't know
your client's name?

40:05.595 --> 40:08.149
I got a call. One of your
prisoners asked for me.

40:08.195 --> 40:10.238
I... didn't get all the details.

40:11.698 --> 40:13.408
You got a name?

40:14.951 --> 40:16.244
Through the opening, please.

40:19.612 --> 40:21.364
- Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

40:22.751 --> 40:24.753
I got a Henry Deaver here.

40:27.505 --> 40:28.964
DEPUTY WARDEN:
I'll find out who called him.

40:29.067 --> 40:31.059
What did Pruitt say?

40:31.176 --> 40:35.041
You don't get on the board by
springing problems on the board.

40:35.222 --> 40:38.308
My job is to fix things.

40:50.445 --> 40:52.696
We're moving to enterprise software,

40:52.783 --> 40:56.697
but the wheels turn slowly,
even in the private sector.

40:56.993 --> 40:59.416
I'm sorry to hear
about your predecessor.

40:59.663 --> 41:02.228
Always heard nice things about him.

41:02.582 --> 41:05.680
My, uh, father worked here.

41:06.044 --> 41:08.305
Visited a lot, anyway,
back in the eighties.

41:08.352 --> 41:11.016
- Oh, really? Corrections?
- Ecclesiastes.

41:11.125 --> 41:15.261
Pastor. He led Bible study
from time to time.

41:16.706 --> 41:18.534
Any idea why Warden Lacey would have...

41:18.597 --> 41:19.855
Forced buyout.

41:19.891 --> 41:23.628
Some folks are just not cut out
for the 19th hole.

41:24.170 --> 41:27.506
And some people guillotine
themselves with a Lincoln.

41:27.649 --> 41:29.859
Guess everybody deals
with retirement differently.

41:34.390 --> 41:35.573
What about...

41:37.554 --> 41:39.013
recent transfers?

41:39.390 --> 41:41.704
If he's in here...

41:41.884 --> 41:43.885
he's in there.

41:44.082 --> 41:46.501
I wish I could help you find
your client, Mr. Deaver.

41:46.560 --> 41:48.521
I can't very well call up a ghost.

41:50.213 --> 41:53.048
Thing is, a ghost called <i>me.</i>

41:53.300 --> 41:54.508
From inside this prison.

41:54.752 --> 41:56.468
Your anonymous caller.

41:56.674 --> 41:59.221
And then you flew two thousand miles?

41:59.264 --> 42:00.557
Had some free time.

42:01.599 --> 42:03.101
Mr. Deaver.

42:05.520 --> 42:09.827
The average CO is a 25-year-old
who makes nine dollars an hour.

42:09.899 --> 42:11.945
These guys don't think much of lawyers.

42:12.027 --> 42:15.023
And in a state as lily-white as Maine,

42:15.113 --> 42:18.533
is it possible that you were
a victim of a prank?

42:21.286 --> 42:23.632
If this was a goose chase,

42:24.039 --> 42:27.282
I hope you'll accept my apologies.

42:27.917 --> 42:31.923
And if you happen to find
the missing page from your book,

42:32.339 --> 42:33.829
you'll get in touch.

42:33.965 --> 42:36.216
I assume private prisons

42:36.217 --> 42:38.628
still fall under the purview
of the Constitution.

42:38.720 --> 42:40.362
This isn't Texas, Counselor.

42:40.440 --> 42:42.183
Actually, it would be pretty odd

42:42.229 --> 42:44.503
if we did have one of your clients.

42:44.642 --> 42:47.855
Maine got rid of
the death penalty 150 years ago.

42:48.688 --> 42:50.356
How'd you know I work capital cases?

42:50.421 --> 42:51.788
Sorry?

42:51.816 --> 42:54.132
I didn't say I work capital.

42:54.235 --> 42:57.468
Oh, we don't have gallows here,
but we do have cable news.

42:57.572 --> 42:59.699
I was sorry to hear about your client.

43:17.790 --> 43:20.466
ZALESKI: All right, that's it,
everybody, time's up.

43:20.598 --> 43:22.847
Get in line, better get back in.

43:26.245 --> 43:29.581
<i>♪♪</i>

43:29.607 --> 43:31.025
FEMALE GUARD: This way.

43:50.083 --> 43:53.461
<i>♪♪</i>

44:32.500 --> 44:34.497
MAN ON RADIO:
<i>Three-and one to the hitter.</i>

44:34.627 --> 44:35.857
MAN 2 ON RADIO: <i>He's dancin' around</i>

44:35.904 --> 44:37.388
<i>out there at second base a lot.</i>

44:37.450 --> 44:39.333
<i>He's got 'em really worried about him,</i>

44:39.372 --> 44:41.138
<i>but I don't think he's...</i>

44:41.217 --> 44:42.676
[commentary continues indistinctly]

44:42.677 --> 44:44.095
[sniffs]

44:49.434 --> 44:51.811
<i>♪♪</i>

45:03.740 --> 45:06.034
<i>[sportscast continues]</i>

45:15.627 --> 45:18.337
- [glass clinks]
- [liquid pours]

45:18.338 --> 45:20.715
- [thud]
- ALAN: Whistle dry?

45:23.718 --> 45:25.470
I'm good.

45:32.685 --> 45:35.081
You knew Dale Lacy a long time, right?

45:35.271 --> 45:36.729
The warden?

45:36.814 --> 45:40.135
We weren't exactly handball buddies.

45:40.276 --> 45:42.206
Why did he do it?

45:42.969 --> 45:45.971
This might surprise you,
given your line of work,

45:46.074 --> 45:48.475
but it's not always a happy job,

45:48.576 --> 45:50.569
carryin' the keys.

45:51.496 --> 45:53.924
I got a call from Shawshank.

45:54.502 --> 45:56.509
They found a kid in a cage.

45:57.377 --> 45:58.585
Call from who?

45:59.170 --> 46:00.964
I don't know yet.

46:02.423 --> 46:04.914
What I hear, prison's full of cells.

46:04.968 --> 46:07.762
Not a cell. A cage.

46:11.599 --> 46:13.245
Huh.

46:14.769 --> 46:16.437
Huh?

46:17.730 --> 46:19.690
[sighs]

46:19.691 --> 46:22.909
Henry, I'm just an old-school cop.

46:23.027 --> 46:26.912
Corrections?
That's a whole 'nother world.

46:27.364 --> 46:29.532
Whole 'nother world?

46:29.909 --> 46:31.244
Same blue line.

46:32.579 --> 46:35.330
[scoffs]

46:35.331 --> 46:36.499
[sighs]

46:41.350 --> 46:42.934
You know where he did it?

46:43.482 --> 46:46.702
Castle Lake. The bluff.

46:46.759 --> 46:49.632
Right where I found you.

46:50.263 --> 46:51.848
Damnedest thing.

46:53.016 --> 46:54.225
Huh.

46:58.104 --> 47:00.189
[footsteps recede]

47:09.991 --> 47:12.827
<i>♪♪</i>

47:26.132 --> 47:29.594
<i>♪♪</i>

47:41.981 --> 47:44.609
<i>♪♪</i>

48:09.842 --> 48:12.804
<i>♪♪</i>

48:25.233 --> 48:27.485
<i>[sportscast on radio]</i>

48:44.877 --> 48:47.213
<i>♪♪</i>

49:08.776 --> 49:11.279
<i>[sportscast continues]</i>

49:17.160 --> 49:18.995
<i>♪♪</i>

49:36.387 --> 49:38.389
<i>♪♪</i>

49:55.114 --> 49:57.200
- Shhh... it!
<i>- [alarm ringing]</i>

50:13.549 --> 50:16.511
<i>♪♪</i>

50:19.916 --> 50:22.078
ALAN: <i>Said it was
minus-forty last night.</i>

50:23.389 --> 50:26.809
<i>You know how cold that is?
Freeze to death in an hour.</i>

50:29.398 --> 50:31.901
<i>And you've been gone for eleven days.</i>

50:34.070 --> 50:36.280
<i>So what happened out there?</i>

50:47.458 --> 50:50.461
<i>♪♪</i>

51:11.232 --> 51:14.026
<i>♪♪</i>

51:17.154 --> 51:19.490
[water sloshing]

51:37.383 --> 51:39.385
<i>♪♪</i>

51:42.346 --> 51:43.859
When they find you...

51:44.015 --> 51:46.726
ask for Henry Deaver.

51:53.967 --> 51:57.387
Henry Matthew Deaver.

52:08.247 --> 52:11.000
[metallic door rolls open]

52:14.503 --> 52:16.797
[door slams shut]

